1. From the Rediscovery of Newton’s Rings to Physical Fundamentals — Energy Packet Pixels
1.1 Dilemmas of the Traditional Interpretation
For more than three hundred years since Newton discovered the ring pattern, wave optics has attributed Newton’s rings to optical interference generated by two reflected wave components on the upper and lower surfaces of the air thin film. Although mathematically concise, this explanation leaves fundamental physical contradictions unsolved: why does destructive interference produce an absolute zero light intensity? Why do interference patterns exhibit rigid topological stability? And how can wave-particle duality be logically unified within this system?
1.2 New Clues from Experimental Reobservation
High-precision re-examination of Newton’s rings reveals three overlooked microscopic features that contradict continuous wave assumptions:
Discrete Edge Character: Under high spatial resolution, the boundaries between bright and dark regions present stepped transitions instead of smooth gradients.
Absolute Dark Zones: Under ideal experimental conditions, the center of dark fringes reaches an absolute zero intensity within detection limits, rather than merely a minimum value.
Structural Rigidity: The overall ring pattern, especially fine dark lines inside bright rings, maintains topological stability similar to crystal defects.
These objective observations directly invalidate the continuous wave hypothesis and provide empirical support for the new discrete physical model.
