3. Pixel Projection Interpretation of Newton’s Rings Formation
3.1 Restatement of the Experimental Setup
A plano-convex lens is placed in close contact with a flat glass substrate, forming an air thin film with gradually increasing thickness from the central contact point to the outer edge. In traditional optics, this device is regarded as an interference structure; in this new theory, it functions as a grid excitation regulator.
3.2 Mechanism of Pixel Projection
Thickness-dominated excitation rule:
When the air film thickness matches an integer multiple of the intrinsic energy packet scale, local grid units achieve complete excitation, forming bright pixels and presenting bright rings macroscopically.
When the air film thickness corresponds to a half-integer multiple of the energy packet scale, the region falls into grid gaps where excitation is forbidden; pixels remain unactivated, forming absolute dark rings.
Geometric inevitability of the ring pattern:
Circular Symmetry: The uniform air thickness at the same radial distance ensures synchronous excitation states across the circumference, producing regular circular fringes.
Central Dark Spot: The tight contact at the lens vertex leads to near-zero thickness, falling into the intrinsic grid gap and resulting in a permanent central dark area.
Outer Ring Compression: The increasing thickness gradient in outer regions accelerates the alternation between excited and forbidden zones, reducing the spacing between adjacent rings.
